<FONT CLASS="title16">Pairing with Drinks</FONT><BR>
<font class="bodyCopySmall">  
Every cheese has its wine. Every wine has its cheese. Sometimes beer is just better. 
What do we look for in a match? At the very least, the drink should never 
overpower the cheese, the cheese should never dominate the wine. With a perfect match, 
a marriage of flavors &#151; even a whole new flavor &#151; is created. 
The rules are few, and experimentation is half the fun. 
<P>
<b>The Same Soil, the Same Sky</b><BR>
Pair cheeses with beverages from the same region. They share the soil, the sun, 
the water, and the local tradition. Cheddar with English ale, Crottin with Sancerre, 
Chianti with Pecorino, Parmigiano with Lambrusco. This doesn't always work, 
but it's a good start.
<P>
<b>Fresh and Soft</b><BR>
Delicate, fresh cheeses need crisp and tart or subtly sweet white wines, 
or bubbly champagne.
<P>
<b>Ch&egrave;vres</b><BR>
Ch&egrave;vres, fresh and aged, are superb with crisp, minerally sauvignon blanc. 
Try fully aged ch&egrave;vres with a mature burgundy or other elegant red.
<P>
<b>Brie and Friends</b><BR>
Rich, milky Brie needs some acidity to cut through all that fat. Try crisp, 
toasty champagne or a tangy white. Smellier styles of Brie can take on a 
mature Bordeaux or hard apple cider.
<P>
<b>Stinky Cheeses</b><BR>
The milder of the stinky cheeses cry out for rich Trappist beers. The really 
stinky ones need a dose of the floral perfume of Alsatian gew&uuml;rztraminer 
or German Riesling, or the fruity bite of hard apple or pear ciders.
<P>
<b>Firm Cheeses</b><BR>
Mild, firm cheeses such as Havarti or young Gouda go best with a fruity red or 
a mug of beer. The Swiss and Alpine cheeses call for fragrant country whites. 
Cheddary English cheeses are meant for full-bodied draft ale or even a glass of 
ruby port. Aged sheep's-milk cheeses, like Pecorino or Etorki, are perfect with 
earthy, full-bodied reds or sweet hard ciders.
<P>
<b>Blues</b><BR>
A little sweetness balances the salt and spice of blues, hence the storied 
matchups of Stilton and port, Roquefort and Sauternes.<BR>

